WEBVTT

00:01.560 --> 00:05.098
Previously on Elementary...
Joan Watson,
meet Gareth Lestrade.

00:05.130 --> 00:06.199
My relationship with Lestrade

00:06.240 --> 00:08.094
started as a marriage
of convenience.

00:08.140 --> 00:10.062
Because I prefer to work
in anonymity,

00:10.110 --> 00:11.759
the glory of my casework
was accrued to him.

00:11.810 --> 00:15.803
Over the years, he became
accustomed to the spotlight.

00:15.840 --> 00:17.501
He began to crave it.

00:17.550 --> 00:19.518
You might say,
I turned him into an addict.

00:19.550 --> 00:20.539
I'll thank you not
to take credit

00:20.580 --> 00:22.810
for any of my insights
into the case.

00:22.850 --> 00:25.284
LESTRADE:
I always knew that
Lawrence Pendry

00:25.320 --> 00:28.084
was, in fact, guilty and had
actually murdered his wife.

00:28.120 --> 00:30.554
He called your bluff.

00:32.800 --> 00:37.260
(indistinct conversation,
piano playing mellow jazz)

00:37.300 --> 00:40.463
(phone buzzing)

00:40.500 --> 00:42.434
(indistinct conversation
continues)

00:42.470 --> 00:43.835
(people laughing)

00:43.870 --> 00:45.701
MAN: Sorry. I think
I have a call.

00:45.740 --> 00:47.731
Oh, wait. It's not me.
Is it you?

00:50.210 --> 00:52.440
Hey, I'm back.

00:52.480 --> 00:54.471
(rooster crows)

00:54.520 --> 00:56.112
(roosters clucking)

00:56.150 --> 00:58.311
I was out on a small case
last night.

00:59.790 --> 01:01.485
Yeah, I was just
at the bodega.

01:01.520 --> 01:03.522
Ignacio said
you helped him...

01:03.560 --> 01:06.324
find out where his son
was getting so much cash.

01:06.360 --> 01:07.622
Cockfighting.

01:07.660 --> 01:09.218
I had to break up
the ring, naturally.

01:09.270 --> 01:10.862
Barbaric practice.

01:10.900 --> 01:13.664
So you decided to bring
one of the chickens home?

01:13.700 --> 01:14.860
(loud clucking)

01:14.900 --> 01:18.165
Well, there are two combatants
in a cockfight.

01:18.210 --> 01:20.201
I could have called
Animal Control.

01:20.240 --> 01:21.798
But it occurred to me,

01:21.840 --> 01:23.705
we have an opportunity.

01:23.750 --> 01:25.741
There's some debate
as to whether these creatures,

01:25.780 --> 01:27.771
once perverted by their keepers,
can be weaned

01:27.820 --> 01:29.344
from their aggressive
tendencies.

01:29.390 --> 01:32.518
The process,
as it stands now, is tedious,

01:32.560 --> 01:34.812
highly imperfect-- I believe
it can be improved upon.

01:34.860 --> 01:36.521
I believe that,
by this time,

01:36.560 --> 01:38.187
several days hence,

01:38.230 --> 01:40.824
Romulus and Remus
will be living side by side,

01:40.860 --> 01:43.863
two cocks in harmony.

01:43.900 --> 01:46.437
All right. Good luck.

01:46.470 --> 01:48.461
I'm not feeding them.

01:48.500 --> 01:51.833
You seem upset. Do you have
an aversion to cocks?

01:51.870 --> 01:53.872
Not as a species.
I have an aversion

01:53.910 --> 01:55.309
to these particular...

01:55.340 --> 01:56.773
(clucking continuing)

01:56.810 --> 01:58.300
You know what?

01:58.350 --> 02:00.614
I'm not 12.
I'm not calling them that.

02:00.650 --> 02:02.288
Feed your roosters.

02:02.320 --> 02:04.185
(phone chimes)

02:04.220 --> 02:05.881
It's Captain Gregson.

02:07.260 --> 02:09.387
Wants to meet us immediately.

02:11.590 --> 02:13.922
GREGSON: So, reps from
the Treasury Department

02:13.960 --> 02:16.622
and the Labor Department
were in town from DC.

02:16.670 --> 02:18.820
They were trying
to sell the big banks

02:18.870 --> 02:20.667
on the president's
latest budget,

02:20.700 --> 02:22.736
and someone
detonated a bomb.

02:22.770 --> 02:24.465
Six people are dead.

02:24.510 --> 02:25.932
What kind of explosive?

02:25.970 --> 02:27.904
Bomb squad isn't sure.

02:27.940 --> 02:30.909
It's definitely
homemade, but intricate.

02:43.230 --> 02:44.652
So, the people
from the government were meeting

02:44.690 --> 02:45.884
with the bankers here?

02:47.260 --> 02:49.399
Bomb was under the table...

02:51.300 --> 02:52.437
They were targeted?

02:52.470 --> 02:53.698
We think so, yeah.

02:53.740 --> 02:54.889
One more thing.

02:54.940 --> 02:56.760
Two of the vice
presidents of the bank

02:56.810 --> 02:58.607
that were killed were
from Whitbrook-Balsille.

02:58.640 --> 03:01.302
Richard Balsille, the CEO?

03:01.340 --> 03:04.343
Apparently,
he's got a security czar

03:04.380 --> 03:05.938
on his payroll,

03:05.980 --> 03:07.868
someone who conducts threat
assessments for the company.

03:07.920 --> 03:10.241
Security Czar? Really?
GREGSON: Yeah.

03:10.290 --> 03:11.814
Balsille's got pull
with the mayor,

03:11.850 --> 03:13.579
so, we're supposed
to give his guy

03:13.620 --> 03:16.282
access to the investigation.

03:16.330 --> 03:18.753
Well, sorry...
I refuse, on principle, to work

03:18.790 --> 03:21.998
with anyone who would willingly
refer to themselves as a "czar."

03:22.030 --> 03:24.590
Actually,
you already know him.

03:24.630 --> 03:26.769
The two of you worked together
at Scotland Yard.

03:26.800 --> 03:29.462
Sherlock Holmes.

03:29.510 --> 03:31.865
As I live and breathe.

03:31.910 --> 03:33.468
Lestrade.

03:33.510 --> 03:34.772
Well, I haven't seen you

03:34.810 --> 03:35.970
since you were publicly

03:36.010 --> 03:38.001
claiming credit for my work.

03:38.050 --> 03:39.938
That's one way
of looking at it.

03:39.980 --> 03:41.868
Yes, one accurate way.

03:41.920 --> 03:44.013
Well, who's to say what's
accurate and what's not?

03:44.050 --> 03:45.347
Me.

03:45.390 --> 03:46.379
Watson, if you like.

03:47.490 --> 03:48.514
I always find truth

03:48.560 --> 03:49.458
somewhere in the middle.

03:49.490 --> 03:50.980
Hello, Miss Watson.

03:51.030 --> 03:53.248
Happy to see you again.

03:53.300 --> 03:54.892
Joan. Please.

03:54.930 --> 03:57.319
Uh, but you look good.

03:57.370 --> 03:58.928
Yes, well, I...
I am good.

03:58.970 --> 04:00.790
Gutted about all
of this, of course,

04:00.840 --> 04:03.434
but other than that,
I'm excellent, and delighted

04:03.470 --> 04:04.869
to see the pair of you.

04:04.910 --> 04:06.309
(wry laugh)

04:06.340 --> 04:07.477
So how about it, Holmes?

04:07.510 --> 04:10.843
You ready to match wits?

04:19.320 --> 04:22.426
(camera whirring
and clicking rapidly)

04:22.460 --> 04:25.384
You probably thought
I was on the skids.

04:25.430 --> 04:26.590
Why would you say that?

04:26.630 --> 04:28.291
WOMAN:
Fresh coconut water,

04:28.330 --> 04:30.298
Mr. Lestrade.
Ah, thanks. Lovely.

04:31.930 --> 04:34.364
Healthy stuff.

04:34.400 --> 04:36.937
Good for the rehydration.

04:36.970 --> 04:39.530
That's my assistant, you see--
Miss Truepenny.

04:39.580 --> 04:41.935
Yeah, she wants to be a
consulting detective, too.

04:41.980 --> 04:44.574
She wrote to me

04:44.610 --> 04:46.475
every day, begging
for an interview.

04:46.520 --> 04:48.317
I cracked.

04:48.350 --> 04:51.615
Now, as I recall,
you weren't too keen

04:51.650 --> 04:54.414
about me striking out
on my own, were you?

04:54.460 --> 04:55.916
What, you thought

04:55.960 --> 04:57.723
I couldn't hack it without you,
did you?

04:57.760 --> 04:59.523
That's not precisely
how I put it.

04:59.560 --> 05:01.027
LESTRADE:
Yeah, well, aanay,

05:01.060 --> 05:03.426
Fleet Street took
rather a shine to me

05:03.470 --> 05:05.461
after that whole
Lawrence Pendry thing.

05:05.500 --> 05:09.539
Yeah. I got awful lots of work,
got chat show interviews.

05:09.570 --> 05:12.607
You know, they even asked me
to do one of those DOUG Chats

05:12.640 --> 05:15.006
