06:05.190 --> 06:07.590
I'm sorry. My ears
are still ringing.

06:07.630 --> 06:10.519
That's all right. We appreciate
you talking with us.

06:10.570 --> 06:11.923
You work
with the Department of Labor?

06:11.970 --> 06:13.631
I'm an executive

06:13.670 --> 06:16.059
undersecretary at the Office
of Congressional Affairs.

06:16.100 --> 06:19.672
And you were at the end of the
table when the bomb went off?

06:19.710 --> 06:22.076
That's where executive
undersecretarles go.

06:22.110 --> 06:24.499
Did you notice
anything suspicious?

06:24.550 --> 06:26.609
No, it was just lunch.

06:26.650 --> 06:28.618
Same as we do every quarter.

06:28.650 --> 06:32.654
Sorry. You said, "That's where
executive undersecretaries go."

06:32.690 --> 06:35.955
Was there a prearranged
seating assignment?

06:35.990 --> 06:38.823
Would you mind writing
that out for us?

06:38.860 --> 06:40.657
Seating arrangements?

06:40.700 --> 06:43.692
No offense, mate,
but I think we might be able

06:43.730 --> 06:46.597
to aim a little higher
than that, don't you? Right?

06:46.640 --> 06:50.030
Uh, Miss... Miss Forrester...

06:50.070 --> 06:54.006
now, you say didn't
see anything unusual,

06:54.040 --> 06:55.029
but, in my experience,

06:55.080 --> 06:57.776
memory can prove to be a bit
of a triclq mistress.

06:57.810 --> 06:59.949
Sometimes when I'm interviewing
potential witnesses,

06:59.980 --> 07:04.542
I ask them to do what I
like to call a deep dive.

07:04.590 --> 07:06.854
That's a way of just
shaking loose stuff

07:06.890 --> 07:08.858
that might be lurking
deep down there.

07:08.890 --> 07:13.589
Would you be willing to
perform a dive with me?

07:13.630 --> 07:16.019
Um... sure.

07:16.060 --> 07:17.766
Fabulous.

07:17.800 --> 07:20.189
Um, just give
me your hand.

07:20.240 --> 07:21.798
Now, I want you
to close your eyes...

07:21.840 --> 07:23.034
Watson and I will be off

07:23.070 --> 07:24.765
interviewing
the restaurant manager.

07:24.810 --> 07:26.163
Miss Forrester, if you could
write out that chart for us

07:26.210 --> 07:28.701
when you emerge from the depths.

07:30.510 --> 07:32.148
Take a deep breath.
Don't be s...

07:33.980 --> 07:37.780
I don't think anyone broke into
the place to plant the bomb.

07:37.820 --> 07:39.754
If they did, we didn't notice.

07:39.790 --> 07:42.179
Everything seemed normal
this morning?

07:42.220 --> 07:44.757
Sure.

07:44.790 --> 07:46.223
John had to go home sick,

07:46.260 --> 07:48.125
but after that,
everything was business

07:48.160 --> 07:50.799
as usual.
John?

07:50.830 --> 07:53.139
Yeah, John Bowden.
He's one of our servers.

07:53.170 --> 07:56.799
He came in for about 20 minutes,
then said his stomach was upset.

07:58.840 --> 08:00.808
Is he a contented employee?

08:00.840 --> 08:05.140
He's an okay worker,
but he's a pain in the ass.

08:05.180 --> 08:08.843
He tried to unionize the
dishwashing staff a while back.

08:08.880 --> 08:12.782
He's always talking about how
he can't stand the clientele.

08:13.820 --> 08:15.583
Now, I know that sounds

08:15.620 --> 08:17.827
kind of ominous,

08:17.860 --> 08:20.021
but he's annoying.

08:20.060 --> 08:23.826
He's not a terrorist.

08:23.870 --> 08:26.293
Call us if he
gets there, okay?

08:26.330 --> 08:28.298
Bowden never showed up
to his apartment.

08:28.340 --> 08:30.604
His _roommates have
no Idea where he IS.

08:30.640 --> 08:31.732
LESTRADE: Right.
Now, follow me.

08:31.770 --> 08:32.737
Uh... (clears throat)

08:32.780 --> 08:34.839
Sherlock?

08:34.880 --> 08:37.303
One seating plan-- check.

08:37.350 --> 08:38.908
How do you do?

08:38.950 --> 08:40.918
A waiter with radical leanings

08:40.950 --> 08:42.781
who showed up
for work this morning,

08:42.820 --> 08:45.141
and left ten minutes later.

08:45.190 --> 08:46.782
His name's John Bowden.
(phone ringing)

08:46.820 --> 08:48.185
Oh.

08:48.220 --> 08:50.051
Captain.

08:50.090 --> 08:52.320
GREGSON:
Every publication in the city
with a circulation

08:52.360 --> 08:54.590
over 50,000 just got a statement

08:54.630 --> 08:56.825
taking credit
for the bomb at the restaurant.

08:56.870 --> 08:58.269
I'm gonna test your knowledge.

08:58.300 --> 09:00.336
I'm gonna read you
the first couple lines.

09:00.370 --> 09:02.031
"Soon, you'll be ashes

09:02.070 --> 09:04.937
"or bones, a mere name at most,

09:04.970 --> 09:08.679
_ _ "and even that
IS just a sound, an echo.

09:08.710 --> 09:13.113
The things we want in life
are empty, stale, trivial."

09:13.150 --> 09:14.617
It's from a book
called Meditations.

09:14.650 --> 09:16.015
Yes.

09:16.050 --> 09:18.109
We know. It's not signed,

09:18.150 --> 09:21.688
but it sounds a hell of a lot
like the notes that came in

09:21.720 --> 09:24.723
every time the guy the press
calls Aurelius sets off a bomb.

09:24.760 --> 09:26.250
You know him, right?

09:26.290 --> 09:29.259
Three bombs in ten years,
kissing cousin to the Unabomber.

09:29.300 --> 09:31.621
Yes, of course.
Aurelius espouses

09:31.670 --> 09:35.891
a perversion of Stoic philosophy
as justification for his crimes.

09:35.940 --> 09:38.966
I'm sending you the full text
in an e-mail right now.

09:39.010 --> 09:41.831
Someone just claimed credit
for the bomb.

09:41.880 --> 09:44.303
Right. Aurelius.

09:44.350 --> 09:45.647
So, we're off

09:45.680 --> 09:47.147
to big game now, are we?

09:47.180 --> 09:49.319
There is a Great White
loose in these waters.

09:49.350 --> 09:51.989
Which is it?
Beg your pardon?

09:52.020 --> 09:54.659
Are we hunting game,
or are we fishing for sharks?

09:54.690 --> 09:57.750
'Cause you can't have it both
ways, metaphorically speaking.

09:59.930 --> 10:02.728
LESTRADE:
Like any art form,

10:02.770 --> 10:05.330
the science
of deduction and analysis

10:05.370 --> 10:09.136
requires years of arduous study.

10:09.170 --> 10:11.035
You see, one lifetime
is not enough to master it.

10:11.070 --> 10:13.174
No, no, try several.
So where does one start?

10:13.210 --> 10:15.678
Well, if you want my advice,
you start straightaway...

10:15.710 --> 10:16.972
WATSON:
Take-out's downstairs.

10:17.010 --> 10:18.898
LESTRADE:
...with a simple problem.

10:18.950 --> 10:21.874
But you might be too,
uh, busy working to eat.

10:21.920 --> 10:23.217
It's revolting, isn't it?

10:23.250 --> 10:24.740
My name is Gareth Lestrade,
and I headed up...

10:24.790 --> 10:25.916
A room full
of people so accustomed

10:25.950 --> 10:27.383
to their own flatulence,

10:27.420 --> 10:29.081
they don't notice
the stench anymore.

10:29.120 --> 10:32.180
Lestrade treated you like crap,
he took credit for your work.

10:32.230 --> 10:33.891
He uses your words
in his interviews.

10:33.930 --> 10:35.750
If it bothers you, you
should say something to him.

10:35.800 --> 10:37.665
To what end?

10:37.700 --> 10:40.794
The man has chosen vanity and
the pursuit of the spotlight.

10:40.840 --> 10:43.058
Nothing I say is going
to change that.

10:43.110 --> 10:44.429
It's not about
changing him.

10:44.470 --> 10:45.869
It's about putting
it out there,

10:45.910 --> 10:47.138
so you can focus
on finding Aurelius,

10:47.180 --> 10:49.068
instead of watching
Lestrade yammer.

10:49.110 --> 10:51.442
When_we first ran
Into hIm, you said

10:51.480 --> 10:55.211
that you expected him to
crash and burn without you.

10:55.250 --> 10:56.410
Did you?

10:56.450 --> 10:58.281
I didn't give it much thought.

10:58.320 --> 10:59.719
Oh.

10:59.760 --> 11:01.785
Yes, of course I did.

11:01.820 --> 11:04.129
So, are you mad that he's
still stealing your act,

11:04.160 --> 11:07.698
or annoyed that he managed
to pull it off?

11:07.730 --> 11:07.752
What I do is not an act.

11:11.070 --> 11:12.025
And I'm not pursuing Aurelius

11:12.070 --> 11:13.059
because I no longer believe

11:13.100 --> 11:14.328
that finding that man is going

11:14.370 --> 11:15.792
to help us solve
this particular bombing.

11:15.840 --> 11:18.308
What, you think
the note is a fake?

11:18.340 --> 11:19.978
I can't be certain.

11:20.010 --> 11:22.376
The notes that accompanied
Aurelius's original crimes

11:22.410 --> 11:24.298
were deranged,
but they were consistent

11:24.350 --> 11:26.147
in their interpretation
of Stoicism.

11:26.180 --> 11:28.375
This latest one reads
like the author

11:28.420 --> 11:31.309
spent all of five minutes
researching the philosophy.

11:31.350 --> 11:34.148
Also, the actual Aurelius
never quoted directly

11:34.190 --> 11:36.078
from the Meditations.

11:37.430 --> 11:39.318
That waiter's not much
of a suspect eIther.

11:39.360 --> 11:42.158
I read his blog. He's just...
dabbling in radical thought.

11:42.200 --> 11:43.997
Probably be working
at Whitbrook—Balsille

11:44.030 --> 11:45.497
in ten years.

11:45.530 --> 11:48.237
No... I'm fairly certain
someone is trying to send us

11:48.270 --> 11:49.806
on a wild goose chase.

11:49.840 --> 11:53.276
The actual bomber
lies elsewhere.

11:53.310 --> 11:57.770
Maybe he's in the audience
at the DOUG Chat.

12:02.850 --> 12:06.308
(clucking)

12:06.350 --> 12:08.716
(footsteps approaching)

12:09.960 --> 12:12.087
(sighs)
I guess I should be happy

12:12.130 --> 12:13.495
they're not crowing.

