which stands to reason--
they were seated directly

12:58.870 --> 13:00.406
in the pathway
of the payload of shrapnel.

13:00.440 --> 13:03.079
So you think whoever set off
the bomb was

13:03.110 --> 13:05.271
targeting one or more
of those three?

13:05.310 --> 13:08.108
Mm... Vaughn Antonelli is
a career bureaucrat.

13:08.150 --> 13:09.947
He is a representative
of the federal government

13:09.990 --> 13:11.946
but wields little actual power.

13:11.990 --> 13:13.548
Christine Danoff
was Lawrence Iver's

13:13.590 --> 13:15.979
underling at Whitbrook—Balsille.
Mr. Iver presents

13:16.020 --> 13:18.557
a more interesting case study.
He was known

13:18.590 --> 13:21.423
as a "comer" in banking circles.
And it was widely considered

13:21.460 --> 13:24.327
that he would one day hold
a CEO title of his own.

13:24.370 --> 13:27.931
Hey, who's Jacques St. Teton?

13:27.970 --> 13:29.961
I don't know.

13:30.010 --> 13:32.604
The Griffin Hotel is attached
to the restaurant,

13:32.640 --> 13:35.131
and they provided a list
of their registered guests

13:35.180 --> 13:37.501
the night before the attack,
so we could determine
whether the bomber

13:37.550 --> 13:39.506
was using the hotel
as part of his plan.

13:39.550 --> 13:41.939
Jacques St. Teton
is the only name which really

13:41.980 --> 13:43.447
stands out.
Obvious fake.

13:43.490 --> 13:45.845
There's no St. Teton,
for one thing.

13:45.890 --> 13:49.485
(phone rings)

13:49.520 --> 13:50.487
Sherlock Holmes.

13:50.530 --> 13:52.327
I have Gareth Lestrade for you.

13:52.360 --> 13:53.998
(toilet flushing over phone)
Yes, if you could...

13:54.030 --> 13:56.828
(toilet continues flushing)

13:58.930 --> 14:00.591
Holmes. Hi. Yeah.

14:00.640 --> 14:03.859
I'm trying to get a line on
that John Bowden, the waiter.

14:03.910 --> 14:05.935
I don't know. Got a hunch.
But I figure in some way

14:05.970 --> 14:07.574
he's connected
to Aurelius.

14:07.610 --> 14:09.635
We no longer think that Aurelius
had anything to do

14:09.680 --> 14:11.875
with the attack. I'm currently
focusing my efforts

14:11.910 --> 14:14.879
on the possibility that
Lawrence Iver was the target.

14:14.920 --> 14:18.287
What? Uh, Iver?

14:18.320 --> 14:20.459
Whitbrook—Balsille Iver?

14:20.490 --> 14:22.458
Yes. We're on our way
over there shortly

14:22.490 --> 14:25.186
to seek an audience
with the CEO.
LESTRADE: No...

14:25.230 --> 14:26.458
Holmes, you can't
just march straight

14:26.490 --> 14:27.957
into Dick Balsille's office.

14:28.000 --> 14:29.968
I'm sure we'll find a way.
Holmes...

14:30.000 --> 14:33.299
Lovely seeing you again. And
good luck finding your waiter.

14:33.340 --> 14:35.991
WATSON:
So, our first stop

14:36.040 --> 14:38.133
is Lestrade's boss?
Who better to school us

14:38.170 --> 14:40.400
on the comings and goings
at Whitbrook—Balsille?

14:40.440 --> 14:42.476
Are you sure there's no part
of you that's doing this

14:42.510 --> 14:43.670
to get under
Lestrade's skin?

14:43.710 --> 14:44.972
(quiet, smug laugh)

14:47.020 --> 14:50.114
Miss Truepenny, shouldn't you
be off hunting Aurelius?

14:50.150 --> 14:52.118
Mr. Lestrade is in
with Mr. Balsille.

14:52.150 --> 14:55.085
They'll be with
you when they can.

15:02.360 --> 15:04.521
Fancy seeing you here.

15:04.570 --> 15:07.334
Now, you behave yourself
in there, Holmes.

15:07.370 --> 15:09.167
I assure you: I want only
to catch a bomber.

15:09.200 --> 15:11.964
I have no interest in
compromismg your employment.

15:16.710 --> 15:18.678
Uh, excuse me.

15:18.710 --> 15:21.076
Assistants wait out here.

15:21.120 --> 15:23.611
Right.

15:27.420 --> 15:29.479
Consulting for the NYPD.

15:29.520 --> 15:31.158
Good for you.

15:31.190 --> 15:34.728
I admire people who can make it
work in the public sector.

15:34.760 --> 15:37.160
And Gareth here says
that you guys think

15:37.200 --> 15:39.998
this Aurelius thing
may be just a smokescreen.

15:40.040 --> 15:43.669
Well, like I-I said, Dick,
we're exploring the possibility.

15:43.710 --> 15:45.507
Uh, um...

15:45.540 --> 15:49.169
We think one of your executives
may have been targeted.

15:49.210 --> 15:53.749
How did Lawrence Iver fit
into the hierarchy here?

15:53.780 --> 15:55.577
Larry?

15:55.620 --> 15:57.588
He was an ace.

15:57.620 --> 16:00.180
Started out in Dallas.
He made our clients a boatload

16:00.220 --> 16:03.121
trading
distressed debt.

16:03.160 --> 16:04.718
Came here to the mother ship
five years ago.

16:04.760 --> 16:07.524
He had been on the_commodities
desk ever Since.

16:07.560 --> 16:10.324
Did he have any enemies
at the company?

16:10.370 --> 16:12.167
I guess.

16:12.200 --> 16:13.690
We all do.

16:13.740 --> 16:16.038
Larry told people who
came to work for him:

16:16.070 --> 16:19.733
you eat what you kill
here or you starve.

16:19.770 --> 16:21.431
And some people respond to...

16:21.480 --> 16:23.300
that pressure
and some people simply wilt.

16:23.350 --> 16:24.749
Excuse me,
what are you doing?

16:24.780 --> 16:26.771
Is this your book?

16:26.810 --> 16:29.677
Yes, it is.
Hmm.

16:29.720 --> 16:32.018
I spent two summers
as a fire watcher

16:32.050 --> 16:33.358
at Grand Teton National Park.

16:33.390 --> 16:34.755
HOLMES:
Why?

16:34.790 --> 16:37.020
Sorry. Could I speak
with you

16:37.060 --> 16:38.550
outside for a moment?

16:45.070 --> 16:46.765
Why was your boss doing
at the Griffin Hotel

16:46.800 --> 16:49.735
under an assumed name,
the night before the bombing?

16:49.770 --> 16:51.067
What?

16:51.110 --> 16:52.634
"Jacques St. Teton."
Sound familiar?

16:52.670 --> 16:54.376
If it doesn't,
I'll just ask him.

16:54.410 --> 16:56.037
Oh, you-you'll do
no such thing.

16:56.080 --> 16:57.502
Truepenny, just go,
just go get security.

16:57.550 --> 16:58.778
On it.
You're kicking
us out?

16:58.810 --> 17:00.209
Lawrence _Iver
was a potential CEO.

17:00.250 --> 17:01.649
Your boss is a current CEO.

17:01.680 --> 17:02.749
You can see how
he might feel threatened.

17:02.780 --> 17:05.578
I knew it-- you can't stand
the fact that I've built

17:05.620 --> 17:07.087
something for myself,
can you?

17:07.120 --> 17:08.451
That is a great man
in there,

17:08.490 --> 17:10.458
and I'm not gonna
have you harass him

17:10.490 --> 17:11.582
because you've got some kind
of bizarre beef with me.

17:11.630 --> 17:14.019
Gentlemen, please.

17:18.870 --> 17:23.432
Mr. St. Teton checked in just
after 7:00. I wasn't on duty

17:23.470 --> 17:26.359
that night. Let me see
ifI can find the footage.

17:28.440 --> 17:30.203
Here we go.

17:39.220 --> 17:41.450
Lestrade is
"Jacques St. Teton?"

17:41.490 --> 17:44.288
HOLMES: Or he handled
the check-in for his boss.

17:44.330 --> 17:49.358
Either way, he's more than
just an annoyance now.

17:49.400 --> 17:51.220
_ He's involved
in this somehow.

17:57.840 --> 17:59.865
WATSON:
Okay, just so I'm clear,

17:59.910 --> 18:01.207
you don't think
your ex-partner

18:01.240 --> 18:03.299
helped plan
a mass murder, do you?

18:03.350 --> 18:05.306
Not wittingly.
He may have been duped

18:05.350 --> 18:09.172
into renting the room
without being privy
to the larger plan.

18:09.220 --> 18:10.847
Maybe. Or it could have
nothing to do

18:10.890 --> 18:13.358
with the murders.
I mean,

18:13.390 --> 18:15.187
would the room have been
a convenient place

18:15.220 --> 18:16.448
to assemble a bomb? Sure.

18:16.490 --> 18:19.288
But the guy
is a Wall Street CEO.

18:19.330 --> 18:21.457
I mean, if he wanted
to get rid of someone,

18:21.500 --> 18:23.365
there are easier ways to do it.

18:23.400 --> 18:25.561
We-We could show Balsille
this tape, see what he says.

18:25.600 --> 18:28.137
We've already given him the
opportunity to be forthright.

18:28.170 --> 18:30.638
(doorbell ringing)

18:33.710 --> 18:36.338
All right if I come in?

18:38.210 --> 18:41.270
I owe you an apology.

18:41.320 --> 18:45.381
You've got your process,
and I've got mine.

18:45.420 --> 18:47.559
We've got to accommodate
each other,

18:47.590 --> 18:48.750
I realize that now.

18:48.790 --> 18:52.157
I got territorial.

18:52.190 --> 18:55.159
I was wrong,
and I'm-I'm sorry.

18:56.700 --> 18:58.292
Apology accepted.

18:58.330 --> 19:00.195
(Lestrade stammers)

19:06.410 --> 19:09.402
So, did you find out anything
interesting today?

19:09.440 --> 19:11.647
No.

19:11.680 --> 19:14.911
Unfortunately, the hotel had
already recorded over

19:14.950 --> 19:17.282
the footage of
Jacques St. Teton checking in.

19:17.320 --> 19:22.280
Look, I'm gonna save us
all a little bit of time here.

19:22.320 --> 19:24.788
I meant what I said earlier
around about Richard Balsille

19:24.830 --> 19:27.924
being a-a great man,
but unfortunately,

19:27.960 --> 19:29.689
that doesn't always mean
a good one.

19:29.730 --> 19:34.429
Yeah, he has a tendency
to step out on his wife.

19:34.470 --> 19:36.392
Books himself a room.

19:36.440 --> 19:38.806
And we don't know about anything
till it's done.

19:38.840 --> 19:41.729
Well, thanks for
clearing that up.

19:41.780 --> 19:43.577
Yeah, well, it's important

19:43.610 --> 19:44.941
that we're not rowing in
different directions here.

19:44.980 --> 19:48.472
You know,
you might be right.

19:48.520 --> 19:50.818
about Aurelius's note
being a fake.

19:50.850 --> 19:52.715
But that waiter, John Bowden--
I mean, he disappears

19:52.750 --> 19:54.809
ten minutes _
before the exp|05ion,

19:54.860 --> 19:56.657
and then he drops off
the face of the planet.

19:56.690 --> 19:58.624
I mean, he could have
done it on his own.

19:58.660 --> 20:01.959
Well, we can't rule it out
until we've found the man.

20:02.000 --> 20:04.924
Agreed.

20:04.970 --> 20:09.361
So, to a new spirit
of cooperation then, Holmes?

20:13.410 --> 20:14.672
(chuckles)

20:15.940 --> 20:17.544
I'd suggest a toast,

20:17.580 --> 20:18.877
but we haven't got
any coconut water.

20:22.820 --> 20:26.381
Well, I guess
this is good night.

20:27.690 --> 20:29.681
Oh, right, yes, uh...

20:29.720 --> 20:30.948
Remarkable man.

20:30.990 --> 20:33.458
You know,
you're very luclq.

20:33.500 --> 20:34.694
What?

20:34.730 --> 20:36.322
Oh, yes, I know.

20:36.360 --> 20:37.861
He could say the same
of you, of course.

20:37.900 --> 20:39.993
Oh, thank you.
I mean,
Miss Truepenny,

20:40.030 --> 20:42.339
she tries, but you know
what they say,

20:42.370 --> 20:45.669
"Good help is hard to find."

20:45.710 --> 20:48.679
A good partner
is actually hard
to find, as well.

20:48.710 --> 20:51.702
Yes, I think about
the money that I pay her--

20:51.750 --> 20:53.775
money in the private sector's
quite obscene...

20:53.820 --> 20:57.688
compared to what us
foot soldiers are used to.

20:57.720 --> 21:01.315
So, anyway, if you want
to discuss anything further,

21:01.360 --> 21:02.987
you need any more information,
please, don't hesitate.

21:03.020 --> 21:05.580
So, give me a call.
Oh.

21:05.630 --> 21:07.894
Thank you.
I will keep that in mind.

21:09.460 --> 21:13.396
I think Lestrade just
tried to recruit me.

21:13.440 --> 21:15.635
"Gareth Lestrade,
Consulting Detective.

21:15.670 --> 21:17.501
When you've eliminated
the impossible." Hmm.

21:17.540 --> 21:18.859
Well, perhaps we can play

21:18.910 --> 21:21.777
this to our advantage.
What did you tell him?

21:21.810 --> 21:22.970
I told him
I'd call him, maybe.

21:23.010 --> 21:24.739
Oh, I also stole his phone.
If you want

21:24.780 --> 21:27.874
to know what he's up to,
it's a good place to start.

21:27.920 --> 21:29.774
I thought you weren't convinced
that the bombing was connected

21:29.820 --> 21:31.082
to the renting
of the hotel room.

21:31.120 --> 21:33.714
I'm not.
Lestrade knew damn well

21:33.760 --> 21:36.888
that Balsille rented that room.
He checked him in.

21:36.920 --> 21:38.854
He lied to us.
I want to know why.

21:39.990 --> 21:41.594
Hmm.

21:41.630 --> 21:44.724
Mmm! Smells good.

21:48.470 --> 21:49.835
What's wrong?

21:49.870 --> 21:52.839
You only make those
when you need to calm down.

21:52.870 --> 21:54.804
I spent several minutes
last night trying

21:54.840 --> 21:56.899
to to work out
Lestrade's password.

21:56.940 --> 21:58.373
Birthday?

21:58.410 --> 22:00.105
The year Tottenham
last won the FA Cup.

22:00.150 --> 22:01.674
Ages ago, by the way.

22:01.720 --> 22:04.484
Anyway, the rest of the evening
was spent reviewing

22:04.520 --> 22:07.557
the contents of the phone.

22:07.590 --> 22:09.080
"Operation Firewall"?

22:09.120 --> 22:10.849
It's the ham-fisted name

22:10.890 --> 22:13.324
that Balsille gave to a project
he handed off to Lestrade.

22:14.700 --> 22:16.588
These are all about
Lawrence Iver.

22:16.630 --> 22:18.029
Mm.

22:18.070 --> 22:22.666
Apparently Balsille
did view the man as a rival.

22:22.700 --> 22:24.463
He had his phones tapped,
he monitored

22:24.510 --> 22:26.432
every e-mail he ever sent--
and with good reason.

22:26.470 --> 22:28.836
Iver was working with members
of the Board of Directors

22:28.880 --> 22:32.668
to have Balsille ousted
from his post as CEO.

22:32.710 --> 22:34.541
WATSON: So he was
planning a coup.

22:35.750 --> 22:37.638
And Balsille
knew about it.

22:39.620 --> 22:42.384
You know, I know you've worked
with Lestrade for a long time,

22:42.420 --> 22:44.024
but it's getting kind of hard
not to think of him

22:44.060 --> 22:45.584
as a straight-up
suspect.

22:45.630 --> 22:48.497
Thus the Yorkshires.
(phone ringing)

22:48.530 --> 22:49.292
Sherlock Holmes.

22:49.330 --> 22:50.763
I have Gareth
Lestrade calling.

22:50.800 --> 22:51.789
Yes?

22:53.670 --> 22:55.968
Holmes.

22:56.000 --> 22:57.661
I found John Bowden.

22:57.710 --> 22:59.530
Well, his grandmother
has an apartment

22:59.570 --> 23:00.969
that's still registered
in her name,

23:01.010 --> 23:02.671
even though she died
three years ago.

23:02.710 --> 23:04.405
So I had, uh, Captain Gregson

23:04.450 --> 23:06.509
send that little fella
down to have a look.

23:06.550 --> 23:08.677
John Bowden was hiding in there.

23:08.720 --> 23:10.779
They're on their way
to the station now.

23:10.820 --> 23:13.584
I'll see you there.

23:13.620 --> 23:15.656
Go to the police station.
Make an excuse tor me.

23:15.690 --> 23:17.749
I shall keep after Lestrade.

23:29.600 --> 23:30.703
Don't.

23:30.740 --> 23:32.537
I'm supposed to meet him.

23:32.570 --> 23:35.471
He takes quiet time before
he sits with a suspect.

23:39.650 --> 23:42.175
I see what you're doing,
you know.

23:42.220 --> 23:43.983
I beg your pardon?

23:44.020 --> 23:46.011
All this... sashaying about,

23:46.050 --> 23:47.608
trying to impress him.

23:47.660 --> 23:49.013
It won't work.
This is my job.

23:51.730 --> 23:52.981
Where's Holmes?

23:53.030 --> 23:54.588
He said to start without him.

23:54.630 --> 23:55.654
Oh, you left this
at our place

23:55.700 --> 23:58.066
last night.

24:04.810 --> 24:06.630
I didn't set off a bomb.

24:06.670 --> 24:08.638
I left work because
I really did feel like

24:08.680 --> 24:09.806
I was coming down
with something.

24:09.840 --> 24:11.239
I stopped off
at my gym

24:11.280 --> 24:12.645
on the way home
to get a massage,

24:12.680 --> 24:13.908
and when it was over,

24:13.950 --> 24:15.770
the bombing stuff
was on the news.

24:15.820 --> 24:18.084
Yeah, well, that's a lot
of old bollocks, isn't it?

24:18.120 --> 24:20.850
I mean, if you didn't do
anything, why were you hiding?

24:20.890 --> 24:22.653
I freaked out
when I saw

24:22.690 --> 24:24.089
that Aurelius
took credit.

24:24.130 --> 24:27.793
Look, I go to
this Web forum, okay?

24:27.830 --> 24:29.092
It's people who started
with Occupy,

24:29.130 --> 24:30.995
but everyone's a little more...

24:31.030 --> 24:32.793
aggressive about change.

24:32.830 --> 24:33.797
Radical.

24:33.840 --> 24:35.091
I used to talk about

24:35.140 --> 24:36.789
the government people
and bankers

24:36.840 --> 24:38.728
that come into the restaurant.

24:38.770 --> 24:40.931
You know, just angry stuff.

24:40.980 --> 24:43.505
So this guy-- he calls himself
Cassius on the site--

24:43.550 --> 24:45.802
he was always asking me to
tell him whenever those lunches

24:45.850 --> 24:47.203
got booked.

24:47.250 --> 24:49.218
Cassius was one of
Marcus Aurelius's generals.

24:49.250 --> 24:50.888
I didn't think
about that at the time.

24:50.920 --> 24:52.148
I just figured
he wanted

24:52.190 --> 24:53.657
to stage a protest
or something.

24:53.690 --> 24:55.783
So I told him.

24:55.820 --> 24:57.117
Then the bomb
goes off,

24:57.160 --> 24:59.128
Aurelius takes credit,
I make the connection,

24:59.160 --> 25:02.652
and I hid, because...
I don't know,

25:02.700 --> 25:03.962
I told him
they were coming.

25:04.000 --> 25:05.627
(knocking on door)
I don't know if that

25:05.670 --> 25:06.864
makes me an accessory
or something...

25:06.900 --> 25:08.299
That's enough, John.
Well, who are you?

25:08.340 --> 25:09.864
Your father retained me.

25:09.900 --> 25:12.300
Look, you guys can search
my computers, whatever.

25:12.340 --> 25:13.807
I don't know how
to make a bomb...

25:13.840 --> 25:15.068
Enough.

25:15.110 --> 25:16.179
No more questions.

25:20.850 --> 25:22.818
(sighs)

25:22.850 --> 25:25.842
This kid read
"killer" to you?

25:35.200 --> 25:36.827
HOLMES:
Hello.

25:36.860 --> 25:39.829
How did you
get in here?

25:39.870 --> 25:43.089
I think you've allowed yourself
to become a bit of a fool.

25:43.140 --> 25:45.802
But in spite of that...

25:45.840 --> 25:47.876
I can't believe
you're so far gone

25:47.910 --> 25:49.901
you'd allow yourself
to be involved in a murder.

25:49.940 --> 25:51.271
Right, so, what?

25:51.310 --> 25:53.278
You... you break in my safe,

25:53.310 --> 25:55.346
do you?
I have video of you

25:55.380 --> 25:56.779
dismantling the security camera

25:56.820 --> 25:58.242
at the Griffin Hotel.

25:58.290 --> 25:59.985
I've got e-mails

26:00.020 --> 26:01.612
which confirm you knew

26:01.660 --> 26:03.878
about Lawrence
Iver's plans

26:03.930 --> 26:06.819
to stage a coup
at Whitbrook—Balsille.

26:06.860 --> 26:08.350
Oh, so, I see.

26:08.400 --> 26:11.164
So I didn't actually
leave my phone

26:11.200 --> 26:12.599
at your house, did I?

26:12.630 --> 26:13.858
No, no,
you nicked it.

26:13.900 --> 26:15.765
Watson did.

26:15.800 --> 26:17.768
I don't think she's coming
to work for you, by the way.

26:17.810 --> 26:19.266
Aanay. . .

26:19.310 --> 26:21.699
now, in your hotel suite,

26:21.740 --> 26:23.037
I find evidence of

26:23.080 --> 26:25.776
a clandestine surveillance
program on Iver.

26:25.810 --> 26:28.370
Detailed notes about
his comings and g0ings.

26:28.420 --> 26:30.217
Now, if I
presented all this

26:30.250 --> 26:31.911
to the police,
I rather think

26:31.950 --> 26:33.110
they'd be inclined
to view you

26:33.150 --> 26:35.880
as a potential conspiracist
in a murder.

26:35.920 --> 26:36.955
Are you?

26:38.790 --> 26:40.018
No.

26:40.060 --> 26:41.948
Oh, come on,
Sherlock,

26:42.000 --> 26:43.968
for God's sakes, I mean,
come on, you know me.

26:44.000 --> 26:45.797
The Lestrade I know would not

26:45.830 --> 26:47.832
summon a helicopter
to travel eight blocks.

26:47.870 --> 26:50.907
Well, you know, I... I might
have been showing off a bit.

26:50.940 --> 26:53.977
Doesn't mean I go round
blowing up lunches, does it?

26:54.010 --> 26:56.672
Now,
Balsille...

26:56.710 --> 26:59.076
he's paranoid.
I mean, all CEO's are.

26:59.110 --> 27:01.317
But he was right to be worried
about Iver, though.

27:01.350 --> 27:03.648
And he asked me to find out
a little something about Iver

27:03.690 --> 27:05.112
that might help
get him fired.

27:05.150 --> 27:06.879
And that's it.

27:06.920 --> 27:08.683
So why did you rent
a hotel room at the Griffin

27:08.720 --> 27:09.812
the night before the explosion?

27:13.730 --> 27:15.322
LESTRADE: Well, I suppose
you get rich enough...

27:15.360 --> 27:17.897
your appetites...

27:17.930 --> 27:22.060
grow right alongside
the size of your portfolio.

27:22.100 --> 27:26.059
Well, the way I heard it...

27:26.110 --> 27:29.307
it started the same way
for Balsille.

27:29.340 --> 27:31.205
Wives of colleagues...

27:31.250 --> 27:33.673
No, we've been over this.
If he was having affairs,

27:33.720 --> 27:34.846
you wouldn't have
bothered to lie.

27:34.880 --> 27:36.677
I haven't even started yet.

27:36.720 --> 27:37.948
Well...

27:42.290 --> 27:44.679
Well, anyway,
it went from...

27:44.730 --> 27:46.948
there to call girls.

27:46.990 --> 27:48.958
Eventually--
and this is way before

27:49.000 --> 27:50.695
I actually started
working with him--

27:50.730 --> 27:52.266
he got bored of them, too.

27:52.300 --> 27:54.791
Yeah, he felt that he deserved

27:54.840 --> 27:56.694
something that
nobody else could get.

27:56.740 --> 27:59.903
Now, the thing is,
about my boss, you see...

27:59.940 --> 28:01.771
he's constantly on the lookout
for someone to sleep with him.

28:01.810 --> 28:03.437
Doesn't matter
who they are.

28:03.480 --> 28:05.448
You know, married women...

28:05.480 --> 28:06.845
even the odd bloke.

28:06.880 --> 28:09.815
But when
he spots one,

28:09.850 --> 28:12.239
he does a little bit
of analysis.

28:12.290 --> 28:15.782
You know... what do they want,
what do they need?

28:15.820 --> 28:17.856
And then he puts
together an offer.

28:17.890 --> 28:20.324
Money.
Access.

28:20.360 --> 28:21.952
Favors.

28:22.000 --> 28:23.991
Proper life-changing stuff,
actually.

28:24.030 --> 28:26.123
So he views
everyone he meets

28:26.170 --> 28:27.364
as a potential
prostitute.

28:27.400 --> 28:28.867
Oh...

28:28.900 --> 28:31.960
Well, the bizarre thing
is actually that...

28:32.010 --> 28:35.400
he's right more often than one
would care to think about.

28:37.910 --> 28:39.172
You see, nobody's doing anything

28:39.210 --> 28:40.472
that they don't
actually agree to,

28:40.510 --> 28:43.980
so technically,
nothing's illegal.

28:44.020 --> 28:46.147
But can you imagine
the scandal if it got out?

28:46.190 --> 28:48.852
I mean, whew! Pfft!
He'd be done.

28:48.890 --> 28:52.018
Well, it's mildly distasteful,
I suppose.

28:53.260 --> 28:56.149
But why all the secrecy?

28:56.200 --> 28:58.498
I'm hardly the type
to go running to the press

28:58.530 --> 29:00.168
with a man's secrets.

29:00.200 --> 29:02.794
I wasn't protecting him.

29:03.870 --> 29:06.065
I was protecting myself.

29:06.110 --> 29:10.274
You see, he doesn't handle
the approach himself.

29:10.310 --> 29:13.074
No, that'd be way too
compromising-- no, you see...

29:13.110 --> 29:15.112
you see, I do.

29:15.150 --> 29:16.970
I make the offer.

29:17.020 --> 29:20.012
I check in to the hotel
so no one sees Dick's face.

29:20.050 --> 29:23.087
No, I wasn't planning a murder.

29:23.120 --> 29:27.056
I was acting as
a rich man's pimp.

29:27.090 --> 29:28.921
And why not tell me?

29:28.960 --> 29:30.791
(scoffs)

29:30.830 --> 29:32.923
Right, so you'd do this
kind of work, would you?

29:32.970 --> 29:34.460
No, of course not.

29:34.500 --> 29:36.297
But isn't it better
I know about it

29:36.340 --> 29:38.467
than I think you're
part of some conspiracy?

29:38.510 --> 29:40.501
Look, I was embarrassed,
Sherlock.

29:40.540 --> 29:42.474
Is that so difficult
to get your brain around?

29:42.510 --> 29:44.842
No, I wanted
you to think

29:44.880 --> 29:47.098
that I was getting
by on talent alone.

29:47.150 --> 29:49.539
I wasn't trying
to cover up a bombing.

29:52.320 --> 29:55.016
I mean, you thought
that I was...

29:55.060 --> 29:56.880
a fool before.

29:58.990 --> 30:00.992
What do you think now?

30:11.040 --> 30:13.008
So Lestrade's boss
isn't a bomber?

30:13.040 --> 30:14.439
It would appear not.

30:14.480 --> 30:16.175
So what is he,

30:16.210 --> 30:18.246
a serial indecent proposer?

30:18.280 --> 30:19.599
Look on the bright side.

30:19.650 --> 30:21.174
At least Lestrade recruited you
for detective work.

30:21.220 --> 30:22.175
It could have been
a very different offer.

30:22.220 --> 30:23.448
Hmm.

30:23.480 --> 30:24.447
Thanks for putting
that in my head.

30:24.490 --> 30:26.412
So how is he?

30:26.450 --> 30:28.452
It couldn't have been easy
for him to admit that.

30:28.490 --> 30:29.855
If he hasn't passed out already,

30:29.890 --> 30:31.619
he's probably sulking.

30:31.660 --> 30:35.391
Lestrade's deceptions were
a time-consuming dead end.

30:35.430 --> 30:37.125
We have a murderer to catch.

30:37.160 --> 30:38.559
I watched the video of your
interview with John Bowden.

30:38.600 --> 30:39.965
I found his claims

30:40.000 --> 30:41.558
to have inadvertently passed

30:41.600 --> 30:43.192
the information on to Aurelius
qUIte interesting.

30:43.240 --> 30:45.401
I thought Aurelius's
letter was a fake.

30:45.440 --> 30:46.600
It doesn't read like the man,

30:46.640 --> 30:48.073
but it's quite possible
he wasn't doing

30:48.110 --> 30:49.532
his best work that day.

30:49.580 --> 30:50.569
In any case, I thought
I would ask him myself.

30:50.610 --> 30:52.043
So I had
the department send over

30:52.080 --> 30:53.399
their files
on Aurelius.

30:53.450 --> 30:55.213
The FBI has had a task force

30:55.250 --> 30:57.070
searching for Aurelius
for years.

30:57.120 --> 30:58.940
You think you're just going
to look through a bunch of

30:58.990 --> 31:00.844
NYPD files and find him,
just like that?

31:02.190 --> 31:04.988
Hmm. Of course you do.

31:12.230 --> 31:14.869
(rooster crowing)

31:16.600 --> 31:18.568
(clucking)

31:21.040 --> 31:24.077
Why is Romulus outside my door?

31:24.110 --> 31:25.646
That's Remus.

31:25.680 --> 31:26.999
I don't care
which cock I'm holding,

31:27.050 --> 31:29.518
I just want to know
how it got there.

31:29.550 --> 31:30.676
Okay, congratulations.

31:30.720 --> 31:32.642
You got me to say it.

31:32.690 --> 31:34.954
I don't know if you've
settled on an epitaph yet,

31:34.990 --> 31:36.355
but it does occur to me
that would look
fantastic on a tombstone.

31:36.390 --> 31:38.255
Why is the chicken
outside my door?

31:38.290 --> 31:40.019
To wake you,
of course.

31:40.060 --> 31:41.391
I ran an experiment
last night.

31:41.430 --> 31:43.250
I reached out to
a contact at NASA.

31:43.300 --> 31:45.325
She gained a bit of
notoriety a few years back

31:45.370 --> 31:47.395
when I pointed out
to her the reasons
that Pluto is, in fact,

31:47.430 --> 31:49.261
a trans-Neptunian object
rather than a planet.

31:49.300 --> 31:51.165
She was more
than happy

31:51.210 --> 31:53.030
to provide me
with thermal maps

31:53.070 --> 31:55.630
of New York.

31:56.980 --> 31:58.379
They're heat scans
of the city,

31:58.410 --> 32:00.344
performed by satellite,

32:00.380 --> 32:02.644
one week before
attacks by Aurelius.

32:02.680 --> 32:05.945
In 2006,
a bomb exploded

32:05.990 --> 32:07.184
at the offices
of a hedge fund.

32:07.220 --> 32:08.983
Four years ago,
an explosion at

32:09.020 --> 32:11.159
an economic think tank
claimed two lives.

32:11.190 --> 32:12.987
This one is from
one week before

32:13.030 --> 32:14.258
the bombing of
the restaurant.

32:14.300 --> 32:16.621
In every case,
there is a minute

32:16.660 --> 32:21.495
but perceptible heat
spike in Queens

32:21.540 --> 32:23.531
one week before
a bomb goes off.

32:23.570 --> 32:25.037
Each one represents
something burning

32:25.070 --> 32:27.300
at several
thousand degrees.

32:27.340 --> 32:30.173
Now, when we look closer
at the heat spikes,

32:30.210 --> 32:31.700
we see that
they originate

32:31.750 --> 32:34.969
in Woodside,
Queens,

32:35.020 --> 32:36.169
just behind...

32:40.550 --> 32:41.653
...this house.

32:41.690 --> 32:45.057
Well, Aurelius uses
magnesium tape

32:45.090 --> 32:46.489
to detonate his bombs.

32:46.530 --> 32:49.055
That burns at
5,000 degrees.
Mm.

32:49.100 --> 32:51.660
You think he was
testing his fuses.

32:51.700 --> 32:53.565
A man named Mason Caldwell
lives in this house.

32:53.600 --> 32:55.693
He's filed for unemployment
benefits twice,

32:55.740 --> 32:57.696
each time after being
fired from his job

32:57.740 --> 32:59.401
at an engineering firm.

32:59.440 --> 33:01.738
You found Aurelius.

33:08.150 --> 33:10.141
(knocking on window)

33:10.180 --> 33:11.408
You forgot to call me.

33:11.450 --> 33:12.610
Just...
(grunts)

33:12.650 --> 33:15.619
(door opens)

33:15.660 --> 33:18.128
(door closes)

33:18.160 --> 33:19.286
Must've been an oversight.

33:19.330 --> 33:20.627
Mm.

33:20.660 --> 33:23.151
Gregson, he gave
me the heads up.

33:23.200 --> 33:24.690
Morning, Miss Watson.

33:24.730 --> 33:26.721
Mm. Morning.

33:26.770 --> 33:30.991
So, you decided
to find Aurelius.

33:32.370 --> 33:34.509
And here we are.

33:34.540 --> 33:36.679
May I remind you
this is a good thing.

33:36.710 --> 33:38.348
I pursued a theory--

33:38.380 --> 33:40.507
developed by you, I might add--

33:40.550 --> 33:43.314
and now we might be on the
verge of a breakthrough.

33:43.350 --> 33:45.818
You might even call it
a collaboration of sorts.

33:45.850 --> 33:47.317
Yeah, nice try, Sherlock.

33:47.350 --> 33:48.578
I'm not that gullible.

33:48.620 --> 33:50.053
When I told Watson about this,

33:50.090 --> 33:50.784
she was happy.

33:50.820 --> 33:52.458
Please don't bring me into this.

33:52.490 --> 33:53.752
That's the difference
between you and her.

33:53.790 --> 33:55.758
You spend your time
resenting my abilities,

33:55.800 --> 33:57.756
and she spends her time
developing her own.

33:57.800 --> 33:59.427
If you'd had done the same,

33:59.470 --> 34:01.438
you might've built
a practice you were proud of.

34:01.470 --> 34:02.459
(door opens)

34:02.500 --> 34:03.797
No answer.

34:03.840 --> 34:05.364
But he had a few packages

34:05.410 --> 34:06.832
from a chemical supply
at the door.

34:06.870 --> 34:09.737
We texted pictures
of the packages

34:09.780 --> 34:11.839
and the heat signature
over to a judge.

34:11.880 --> 34:13.404
He's issuing a warrant.

34:13.450 --> 34:15.270
We're going in.

34:25.590 --> 34:27.387
Mason Caldwell!

34:27.430 --> 34:29.819
It's NYPD!

34:33.300 --> 34:35.097
Back!

34:35.140 --> 34:36.129
Clear!

34:38.310 --> 34:40.699
As far as we can tell,
the bomb he was making

34:40.740 --> 34:43.436
was supposed to release
a cloud of chlorine gas

34:43.480 --> 34:45.607
after it went off,
something went wrong

34:45.650 --> 34:47.299
while he was experimenting

34:47.350 --> 34:49.272
with the mix,
he inhaled some gas,

34:49.320 --> 34:51.584
and collapsed
on the magnesium tape

34:51.620 --> 34:54.783
while it was still burning.

34:54.820 --> 34:57.380
It doesn't make any sense.

34:57.420 --> 35:00.253
The bomb at the restaurant
had shrapnel in it, not gas.

35:00.290 --> 35:01.894
HOLMES: That's because
Mason Caldwell

35:01.930 --> 35:03.852
wasn't planning an attack
on a restaurant.

35:03.900 --> 35:05.868
He was gonna dispatch this bomb

35:05.900 --> 35:08.164
to a biotech company.

35:08.200 --> 35:10.498
Well, he's been dead
at least a week.

35:10.540 --> 35:12.167
Which means
that Aurelius did not set

35:12.210 --> 35:14.337
that bomb off at the restaurant.

35:18.610 --> 35:22.148
(ringtone playing)

35:22.180 --> 35:23.875
Uh... are you...?

35:26.220 --> 35:28.586
Are you gonna
answer that or...?

35:30.860 --> 35:32.418
Oh.
(ringtone stops)

35:32.460 --> 35:34.553
I swear, working with the man

35:34.600 --> 35:36.227
has thrown something
out of calibration.

35:36.260 --> 35:39.388
How else to explain such
a persistent lack of results?

35:39.430 --> 35:41.591
We did find Aurelius.
(ringtone plays)

35:41.640 --> 35:44.564
(ringtone stops)
A by-product
of the investigation.

35:44.610 --> 35:47.204
(ringtone playing)

35:47.240 --> 35:49.538
Did you change
Lestrade's ringtone on my phone?

35:49.580 --> 35:51.673
I decided to revisit the notion
that the three people

35:51.710 --> 35:53.871
who sat in the pathway
of the payload of shrapnel

35:53.910 --> 35:56.219
were potential targets.

35:56.250 --> 35:58.343
The Department
of Labor bureaucrat

35:58.390 --> 35:59.880
was happily married,
by all accounts

35:59.920 --> 36:01.182
mild and pleasant.

36:01.220 --> 36:02.517
The Whitbro_ok-Balsil|e
executive...

36:02.560 --> 36:04.448
(ringtone playing)

36:04.490 --> 36:06.219
(ringtone stops)
The Whitbrook—Balsille
executives

36:06.260 --> 36:07.454
were beef-witted sociopaths

36:07.490 --> 36:08.752
who had sold the world
on the idea

36:08.800 --> 36:10.199
that playing Three-card Monte

36:10.230 --> 36:11.697
was somehow _
a respectable profe55ion.

36:11.730 --> 36:13.322
But they're hardly alone
in that, are they?

36:13.370 --> 36:14.439
(doorbell ringing)

36:14.470 --> 36:15.664
(knocking on door)

36:17.570 --> 36:21.233
We're not picking up the phone
because we're working.

36:21.280 --> 36:22.770
Who'd you tell, Holmes?

36:22.810 --> 36:24.505
Who did I tell what?

36:24.550 --> 36:26.802
About Balsille, what he
gets up to in his spare time.

36:26.850 --> 36:27.578
Apart from Watson, nobody.

36:27.610 --> 36:29.840
Well, who'd you tell?
No one.

36:29.880 --> 36:32.246
I only told you.
I mean, somebody must've told.

36:32.290 --> 36:33.848
Now, I've got to find them
or I'm gonna get fired.

36:33.890 --> 36:35.414
Wh-what are you talking about?!

36:35.460 --> 36:37.382
This! Someone,
a couple of hours ago,

36:37.420 --> 36:39.581
sent Balsille
a blackmail threat.

36:39.630 --> 36:41.655
Claiming they know
all about his conquests--

36:41.700 --> 36:43.554
dates, names, times.

36:43.600 --> 36:44.692
Everything!

36:46.730 --> 36:48.891
Whoever's doing this,
they don't want money.

36:48.940 --> 36:51.500
Well, not exactly.

36:51.540 --> 36:52.632
No, they want
Balsille to arrange

36:52.670 --> 36:53.762
for hundreds of stock trades

36:53.810 --> 36:56.233
to be made
by a week this Friday.

36:56.280 --> 36:57.975
Some stocks, some bonds,

36:58.010 --> 36:59.773
some US. currency.

36:59.810 --> 37:01.243
And to disguise it,
they want to spread

37:01.280 --> 37:02.440
the trades across
all diViSions.

37:02.480 --> 37:03.742
Why?

37:03.780 --> 37:06.419
I don't know.

37:06.450 --> 37:08.589
Well, there's money
in there somewhere.

37:08.620 --> 37:10.679
The threat says
a week from Friday

37:10.720 --> 37:12.722
specifically.

37:12.760 --> 37:14.250
Yeah, Balsille's gonna
blame me for the leak.

37:14.300 --> 37:15.824
(laughs)

37:15.860 --> 37:17.396
I'm sorry.

37:17.430 --> 37:18.692
I've just told you
I'm gonna lose my job.

37:18.730 --> 37:20.960
And you find
that funny, do you?
No, not at all.

37:21.000 --> 37:22.592
It's just I've learned that the
government's monthly jobs report

37:22.640 --> 37:23.664
is due out next Friday.

37:23.700 --> 37:25.361
Wait... so?

37:25.410 --> 37:27.264
I'm fairly certain
that this threat is connected

37:27.310 --> 37:28.607
to the bombing
at the restaurant.

37:28.640 --> 37:29.971
I can also say
with near certainty

37:30.010 --> 37:32.808
who is responsible
for both crimes.

37:47.660 --> 37:50.026
We know who's blackmailing you.

37:50.060 --> 37:53.063
In fact, it's the same person
who blew up that restaurant.

37:53.100 --> 37:55.591
What? What are they doing here?

37:55.640 --> 37:57.892
Well, I'll let him tell you.

37:57.940 --> 37:59.498
It's his solve.

37:59.540 --> 38:01.576
He's quite a remarkable
detective, actually.

38:01.610 --> 38:02.770
Maybe I should hire him.

38:02.810 --> 38:04.038
Vaughn Antonelli was one

38:04.080 --> 38:05.445
of the victims
of the bombing.

38:05.480 --> 38:06.447
He was also the chairman

38:06.480 --> 38:08.345
of the benefits review board

38:08.380 --> 38:09.711
at the Department of Labor.

38:09.750 --> 38:11.911
It's not a particularly
exalted post.

38:11.950 --> 38:13.941
_ But it does come
With one interesting perk--

38:13.990 --> 38:15.810
the chairman, he's one
of a handful of people

38:15.860 --> 38:17.009
who has early access

38:17.060 --> 38:19.324
to the department's
monthly jobs report.

38:19.360 --> 38:21.521
As I'm sure you're aware.

38:21.560 --> 38:23.824
The markets can be relied upon
to move upwards and downwards

38:23.860 --> 38:25.896
depending
on the report's findings.

38:25.930 --> 38:27.022
Yes. So?

38:27.070 --> 38:28.332
50 the next one comes OUt

38:28.370 --> 38:29.667
a week from Friday.

38:29.700 --> 38:30.962
Whoever's blackmailing you is
looking

38:31.000 --> 38:32.558
to make a bunch of trades

38:32.610 --> 38:34.828
based on whatever's
in that report.

38:34.880 --> 38:37.075
You'd have to see it before
everybody else to do that.

38:37.110 --> 38:39.999
So...

38:40.050 --> 38:42.018
it's someone from Labor.

38:42.050 --> 38:44.348
HOLMES: Do you know
who stands to succeed

38:44.390 --> 38:45.345
Vaughn Antonelli?

38:45.390 --> 38:46.709
A woman

38:46.750 --> 38:48.786
named "Michelle Forrester."

38:50.490 --> 38:51.684
WATSON: Her current job
didn't give her access

38:51.730 --> 38:52.754
to the jobs report.

38:52.790 --> 38:54.929
But now she has it.

38:54.960 --> 38:56.791
She's blackmailing me?
She was at the table

38:56.830 --> 38:58.058
when the bomb went off.

38:58.100 --> 39:00.068
Seated rather conveniently

39:00.100 --> 39:01.931
out of the path of the blast.

39:01.970 --> 39:03.392
If you know
the seating arrangement,

39:03.440 --> 39:05.601
and you're the one
building the explosive,

39:05.640 --> 39:07.938
you can-- and she did--
arrange things

39:07.970 --> 39:10.768
so that her wounds
were relatively minor.

39:10.810 --> 39:11.845
WATSON:
Once Antonelli was gone,

39:11.880 --> 39:13.438
Forrester had his title

39:13.480 --> 39:15.471
and access to the jobs report.

39:15.520 --> 39:16.873
All the pieces were in place.

39:16.920 --> 39:18.547
She could make
the blackmail threat.

39:18.590 --> 39:21.457
To do that,
she would have to know about me.

39:21.490 --> 39:22.855
Amazing.

39:22.890 --> 39:24.448
So, the name, the photograph--

39:24.490 --> 39:25.650
nothing rings a bell?

39:25.690 --> 39:27.487
LESTRADE:
When Miss Forrester

39:27.530 --> 39:29.395
left college, she came here.

39:29.430 --> 39:32.797
She won an internship
with Whitbrook—Balsille.

